		<item>
		<title>
		By: Michael		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/big-project-syndrome#comment-9227</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Michael]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 21 May 2014 17:10:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5846#comment-9227</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I&#039;ve struggled with this issue for quite some time. It began as kind of a lazy&#039;s getaway but it turned into a real problem when I failed to deliver to professors and bosses. So I took the most scientific approach I could. 

Everything that could be reduced to a basic component, should. All of those basic components, which I call nodes btw, should be taken one by one on a timely basis. By timely I mean that rather than saying I have to get done some X number of nodes, you should think in rates. I have to get 2 nodes done per day, for example. I personally like to use a graphical way of picturing it, since often seeing is believing. So in working graphically I&#039;d start with the final product at the very top and keep reducing it into it&#039;s simpler components until those components aren&#039;t reducible anymore. It should look like a Christmas tree, mathematically those are known as ordered trees.

So, applying my approach to your big project I&#039;d say the principal node would be your book. First order nodes would be the chapters of your book. Within each chapter you might have sections, which would be second order nodes. Each section is made up by shorter passages, which would be third order nodes. And then each passage is made up by paragraphs, or fourth order nodes. Each paragraph is made up by sentences, fifth order nodes. And finally, each sentence is made up by words, or constitutive nodes. 

You start the constitutive nodes and work your way into the principal node and, even though you might not accelerate the rate at which you write the words, you might save time by always knowing where you are and where your destination is. And more importantly, what do you have to do to get to your goal.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve struggled with this issue for quite some time. It began as kind of a lazy&#8217;s getaway but it turned into a real problem when I failed to deliver to professors and bosses. So I took the most scientific approach I could. </p>
<p>Everything that could be reduced to a basic component, should. All of those basic components, which I call nodes btw, should be taken one by one on a timely basis. By timely I mean that rather than saying I have to get done some X number of nodes, you should think in rates. I have to get 2 nodes done per day, for example. I personally like to use a graphical way of picturing it, since often seeing is believing. So in working graphically I&#8217;d start with the final product at the very top and keep reducing it into it&#8217;s simpler components until those components aren&#8217;t reducible anymore. It should look like a Christmas tree, mathematically those are known as ordered trees.</p>
<p>So, applying my approach to your big project I&#8217;d say the principal node would be your book. First order nodes would be the chapters of your book. Within each chapter you might have sections, which would be second order nodes. Each section is made up by shorter passages, which would be third order nodes. And then each passage is made up by paragraphs, or fourth order nodes. Each paragraph is made up by sentences, fifth order nodes. And finally, each sentence is made up by words, or constitutive nodes. </p>
<p>You start the constitutive nodes and work your way into the principal node and, even though you might not accelerate the rate at which you write the words, you might save time by always knowing where you are and where your destination is. And more importantly, what do you have to do to get to your goal.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
