		By: Kelly Galloway		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/big-project-syndrome#comment-8564</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Kelly Galloway]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 23 Apr 2014 03:14:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5846#comment-8564</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Great name for this very real syndrome and a good article. 

May I share a strategy that I have used with success? It is from a book called &quot;How to Grow a Business&quot;. In a section about &quot;tackling a major task&quot;, the authors recommend the following (paraphrased): 

Do SOMETHING toward a goal (and it can be almost anything, as long as it&#039;s DOING) to help snap you out of procrastination and back into activity. DON&#039;T FRET over whether you&#039;re doing the RIGHT thing: JUST GET STARTED! 

To this I would add: Repeat as necessary until you have overcome that &quot;starting resistance&quot;. You will soon have the momentum to propel you forward to accomplish a significant portion of the task.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Great name for this very real syndrome and a good article. </p>
<p>May I share a strategy that I have used with success? It is from a book called &#8220;How to Grow a Business&#8221;. In a section about &#8220;tackling a major task&#8221;, the authors recommend the following (paraphrased): </p>
<p>Do SOMETHING toward a goal (and it can be almost anything, as long as it&#8217;s DOING) to help snap you out of procrastination and back into activity. DON&#8217;T FRET over whether you&#8217;re doing the RIGHT thing: JUST GET STARTED! </p>
<p>To this I would add: Repeat as necessary until you have overcome that &#8220;starting resistance&#8221;. You will soon have the momentum to propel you forward to accomplish a significant portion of the task.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
