		<title>
		By: Anna		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/big-project-syndrome#comment-8507</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Anna]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 21 Apr 2014 07:48:19 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5846#comment-8507</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Hi James, 

Your post made me smile. How about you take half an hour and outline to yourself how the book fits in to your life? I have read a total of three of your blog posts, and they all seem to focus on tweaking little things to have bigger and better impact on your (or your readers&#039;) life(s). 

My guess is that the book you are currently writing, is only a part of a bigger picture or system; a system of your believes, your writing, public speaking, your readers, sales..how you want to spend your life, your time at work, your time off work. 

Objectively, if you have a fair bit of potential sales already &quot;in the bag&quot; - which seems to be the case - you will be commissioned to write more books. Publishing houses like sales.  

Therefore, your first book is only a small part of your career as a published writer. And you will be able to apply your own methods on this small part of your life. And you no longer have the need for perfection or cramming it all in - because you can stick some of that stuff into the next book. 

The other thing that works (in addition to changing your mindset as above) is to get a trusted person with reading skills to review your manuscript thus far. It is important that the person is also brutally blunt and honest. You probably have someone like that around. 

Sometimes just changing the order of chapters or a comment &quot;more on this&quot; or &quot;this is dull as anything, cut it out&quot; is enough to break the spell of a blocked mind. 

Good luck. :-)]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi James, </p>
<p>Your post made me smile. How about you take half an hour and outline to yourself how the book fits in to your life? I have read a total of three of your blog posts, and they all seem to focus on tweaking little things to have bigger and better impact on your (or your readers&#8217;) life(s). </p>
<p>My guess is that the book you are currently writing, is only a part of a bigger picture or system; a system of your believes, your writing, public speaking, your readers, sales..how you want to spend your life, your time at work, your time off work. </p>
<p>Objectively, if you have a fair bit of potential sales already &#8220;in the bag&#8221; &#8211; which seems to be the case &#8211; you will be commissioned to write more books. Publishing houses like sales.  </p>
<p>Therefore, your first book is only a small part of your career as a published writer. And you will be able to apply your own methods on this small part of your life. And you no longer have the need for perfection or cramming it all in &#8211; because you can stick some of that stuff into the next book. </p>
<p>The other thing that works (in addition to changing your mindset as above) is to get a trusted person with reading skills to review your manuscript thus far. It is important that the person is also brutally blunt and honest. You probably have someone like that around. </p>
<p>Sometimes just changing the order of chapters or a comment &#8220;more on this&#8221; or &#8220;this is dull as anything, cut it out&#8221; is enough to break the spell of a blocked mind. </p>
<p>Good luck. :-)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
