		By: Rob		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/big-project-syndrome#comment-8470</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rob]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 18 Apr 2014 16:07:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5846#comment-8470</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Lots of good info posted above and hopefully it will help. 

I am currently faced with a very big and financially important project as well. Reading this hit home on a few levels about knowing you can do it but your not sure why it isn&#039;t happening was the same for me. 

I needed to get back to my old way of figuring myself out. Which for me is to spend a quiet session(s) of asking myself &quot;why&quot; am I behaving in this manner. Then think about that answer for a bit and ask yourself &quot;why&quot; again. This will be repeated maybe 4-7 times until I feel I understand the deeper meaning of my behavior via my subconscious thoughts. 

It is very easy to fool and ignore our inner thoughts by busying the ever present logical mind with action. If you want to truly understand your reason(s) then spend some time getting to know yourself. The clarity from this exercise will be all you need to either move forward or rethink your underlying motivation.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Lots of good info posted above and hopefully it will help. </p>
<p>I am currently faced with a very big and financially important project as well. Reading this hit home on a few levels about knowing you can do it but your not sure why it isn&#8217;t happening was the same for me. </p>
<p>I needed to get back to my old way of figuring myself out. Which for me is to spend a quiet session(s) of asking myself &#8220;why&#8221; am I behaving in this manner. Then think about that answer for a bit and ask yourself &#8220;why&#8221; again. This will be repeated maybe 4-7 times until I feel I understand the deeper meaning of my behavior via my subconscious thoughts. </p>
<p>It is very easy to fool and ignore our inner thoughts by busying the ever present logical mind with action. If you want to truly understand your reason(s) then spend some time getting to know yourself. The clarity from this exercise will be all you need to either move forward or rethink your underlying motivation.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
